Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Peel, core, and dice @Granny Smith Apple{1}(peeled, cored and diced into ½-inch pieces). Quarter @Lemon{1}(quartered). Trim and thinly slice @Scallions{2}(trimmed and thinly sliced).

Place @Maple Pork Breakfast Sausage{10%ounce} on one side of a lightly oiled #baking sheet{} (for 4 servings, arrange across entire sheet). Roast on top rack until browned and cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a #small pot{}, combine apple with ¼ cup water (½ cup for 4 servings) over medium-high heat. Bring to a simmer, then reduce heat to low. Cook, stirring occasionally, until apple is softened, ~{6-8%minutes}. Add @Brown Sugar{1%tablespoon}, @Butter{1%tablespoon}, a squeeze of lemon juice, and a pinch of @Salt{pinch} (2 TBSP butter, a big squeeze of lemon juice, and a big pinch of salt for 4). Increase heat to medium-high; cook, stirring, until compote is thickened and apple is glazed, ~{30-60%seconds} more. Remove from heat and cover to keep warm.

Once sausage is almost done roasting, carefully add @Belgian Waffle{2} to opposite side of sheet; return to top rack until waffles are toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}. (For 4 servings, leave sausage roasting; toast waffles on a second #baking sheet{} on middle rack.)

While waffles toast, heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{2%teaspoon} in a large, preferably nonstick, pan over medium-high heat. Crack @Eggs{4} into pan and cover. (For 4 servings, you may want to cook eggs in batches.) Fry eggs to preference. Season with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Reheat apple compote over medium-high heat if necessary.

> TIP: If compote appears oily, add 1 TBSP water and bring to a boil while stirring to smooth it out.

Divide sausage, eggs, and waffles between plates. Top waffles with apple compote and @Sliced Almonds{1/2%ounce}. Sprinkle scallions over eggs and serve.

> Breakfast Sausage is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.

> Wash hands and surfaces after handling raw eggs. Consuming raw or undercooked eggs may increase your risk of foodborne illness.